I think it=E2=80=99s useful to make a distinction between virtual and augme=
nted reality. Just look at the names: =E2=80=9Cvirtual=E2=80=9D reality is =
about an immersive experience completely disconnected from one=E2=80=99s cu=
rrent reality, while =E2=80=9Caugmented=E2=80=9D reality is about, well, au=
gmenting the reality in which one is already present. This is more than a s=
emantic distinction about different types of headsets: you can divide nearl=
y all of consumer technology along this axis. Movies and videogames are abo=
ut different realities; productivity software and devices like smartphones =
are about augmenting the present. Small wonder, then, that all of the big v=
irtual reality announcements are expected to be video game and movie relate=
d.

Augmentation is more interesting: for the most part it seems that augmentat=
ion products are best suited as spokes around a hub; a car=E2=80=99s infota=
inment system, for example, is very much a device that is focused on the cu=
rrent reality of the car=E2=80=99s occupants, and as evinced by Ford=E2=80=
=99s announcement, the future here is to accommodate the smartphone. It=E2=
=80=99s the same story with watches and wearables generally, at least for n=
ow.

I highlight that timing reference because it=E2=80=99s worth remembering th=
at smartphones were originally conceived of as a spoke around the PC hub; i=
t turned out, though, that by virtue of their mobility =E2=80=94 by being u=
seful in more places, and thus capable of augmenting more experiences =E2=
=80=94 smartphones displaced the PC as the hub. Thus, when thinking about t=
he question of what might displace the smartphone, I suspect what we today =
think of a =E2=80=9Cspoke=E2=80=9D will be a good place to start. And, I=E2=
=80=99d add, it=E2=80=99s why platform companies like Microsoft and Google =
have focused on augmented, not virtual, reality, and why the mysterious Mag=
ic Leap has raised well over a billion dollars to-date; always in your visi=
on is even more compelling than always in your pocket (as is always on your=
 wrist).

I=E2=80=99ll come back to that last paragraph later on; I don=E2=80=99t thi=
nk it=E2=80=99s quite right, in part because Apple Vision shows that the fi=
rst part of the excerpt wasn=E2=80=99t right either. Apple Vision is techni=
cally a VR device that experientially is an AR device, and it=E2=80=99s one=
